Most scholare are agreed that it wants the natural freshness and frecdom of Homer, while it exhibits a degree of art, elegance‚ and majesty never attempted in any poem, save the Georgics of its author. It may, however, be pertinent to remark, that, smooth and uniform as its surface seems, it is really, in great measure, mosaic. That Vir-gil should have translated whole passages out of Homer, or even the Alexandr-ine writers, is no matter of cen- sure: he and his contemporaries would have thought the absence of such “ purpurei panni '' a defect3 and the high authorities of Dante, Ariosto, Tasso, Spenser, Camoens, and Milton ratify their opinion. But the same cannot be said of plagiarisms from Latin authors. How unscrnpulously he appropriated ¹ whole verses of Ennius, of Lucretius, of Lucilius, of even his friend Varius, and of others, the curious reader may find in the VIth Book of Macrobius’s Satur- nalia, which will abundantly repay his perusal. His merit, therefore, in not interfering when others plagiarized his verses, and gained credit by them, is not so great as Donatus would have us believe. It may be right to add that the AEneid is a most conspicuous evidence of the learning, diligence, and anti- quarian research of its illustrious author.
